<h2>Harvard Warns, Others Echo — But Not Everyone Agrees</h2>

<p>If your feed recently featured headlines like "Is AI Dulling Our Minds?" (Harvard Gazette), "Over-Reliance on AI May Harm Your Cognitive Ability" (ScienceAlert), or "Does AI Increase Cognitive Abilities or Decrease Them?" (Frontiers in Psychology), you're not alone in spotting the pattern.</p>

<p>Three independent studies, three different outlets, all pointing to the same concern: <strong>As we grow more comfortable letting AI think for us, are we losing our own ability to think?</strong></p>

<p>This isn't a sci-fi opening. This is a question the academic community is seriously debating in May 2026.</p>

<h2>What Each Source Found</h2>

<h3>Harvard Gazette (May 2026)</h3>

<p>Reporting directly under the title "Is AI Dulling Our Minds?", Harvard's flagship publication cited multiple cognitive scientists and psychologists. The core thesis: as AI tools take on an increasing share of cognitive tasks — from drafting emails to summarizing research papers — the human brain faces a "use it or lose it" risk. Laboratory data suggested a correlation between heavy AI-assisted workflows and diminished critical thinking.</p>

<h3>ScienceAlert (via The Conversation, March 2026)</h3>

<p>Drawing on findings from multiple labs, the analysis operates on two levels:</p>

<ol>
<li>The online environment itself "exploits our cognitive tendencies" — making us more prone to shortcuts and shallow information processing</li>
<li>AI accelerates this process: when AI summarizes for you, drafts for you, and even predicts how someone might reply, the neural circuits responsible for these functions weaken from disuse</li>
</ol>

<p>The key insight: researchers draw a critical distinction between "offloading" (delegating cognitive tasks entirely to AI) and "scaffolding" (using AI as a cognitive support structure to augment your own thinking). Most users are doing the former — often without realizing it.</p>

<h3>Frontiers in Psychology (2026)</h3>

<p>This peer-reviewed paper asks a more nuanced question: does AI increase or decrease cognitive abilities? The answer: it depends on who you are. Individual differences — cognitive style, self-regulation capacity — are the key moderating variables. People with strong self-regulation showed cognitive enhancement with AI support, while those with weaker self-regulation were more prone to cognitive dependency.</p>

<h2>Three Converging Findings</h2>

<h3>Finding 1: The Problem Isn't AI — It's How You Use It</h3>

<p>Each study frames the issue differently, but they converge on the same core judgment: AI itself is not the enemy. What matters is whether the user remains "in control" — actively deciding what to delegate and what to handle personally.</p>

<p>The difference between scaffolding and offloading is the difference between using AI to grow and using AI to replace yourself.</p>

<h3>Finding 2: Correlation Exists — Causation Is Not Yet Proven</h3>

<p>Current research can show that "heavy AI users perform differently on certain cognitive metrics," but it cannot yet prove that AI <em>causes</em> cognitive decline. It may be that people with weaker cognitive tendencies are simply more likely to choose AI substitutes for thinking. This is the "couch potato" problem: does the couch make you fat, or do people prone to weight gain naturally gravitate toward the couch?</p>

<h3>Finding 3: Individual Differences Matter More Than You Think</h3>

<p>Frontiers' research shows that AI's cognitive impact is not uniform. Self-regulated individuals experience cognitive enhancement with AI; the less regulated experience degradation. This isn't a question of "AI is bad for everyone" or "AI is good for everyone" — it depends entirely on your starting cognitive habits.</p>

<h2>A Better Question to Ask</h2>

<p>The question "Does AI make us dumber?" has a more useful version: <strong>"Is the way we're using AI training us to become better thinkers?"</strong></p>

<p>One observation the Harvard article doesn't make explicitly: people who feel "AI is making me dumber" often aren't victims of AI doing something wrong. Rather, AI has <strong>revealed a cognitive laziness that was already there</strong>. In the pre-AI era, these individuals weren't thinking any deeper — there just wasn't a mirror showing them how shallow their thinking actually was.</p>

<p>To borrow a conclusion from the companion piece on today's humanaifit site: <strong>AI is a mirror. Give it the role of a crutch, and it will show you what dependence looks like. Give it the role of a coach, and it will show you what growth looks like.</strong></p>

